Eigen Faces and PCA linear dimention reduction¶

PCA implementation¶

To implement calss PCA, implementing methods fit and transform. Class requires n_components parameter in the constructor.

In [ ]:
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline

# write your code here
class PCA:
  def __init__(self,n_components):
    self.n_components = n_components
  def fit(self,X):
    centered_X = X-np.mean(X,axis=0)
    eigvals, eigvecs = np.linalg.eigh(np.cov(centered_X,rowvar=False))
    sorted_eigs_ind = np.argsort(eigvals)[::-1]
    sorted_eigvals = eigvals[sorted_eigs_ind]
    sorted_eigvecs = eigvecs[:,sorted_eigs_ind]
    self.pcs = -sorted_eigvecs[:,0:self.n_components]
  def transform(self,X):
    centered_X =  X-np.mean(X,axis=0)
    return np.dot(self.pcs.T,centered_X.T).T

Now, create some dataset using sklearn and implement fit and transform of your class at created data.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.datasets import load_breast_cancer
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
data=load_breast_cancer()
print(*data['feature_names'],sep=', ')
df=pd.DataFrame(data['data'],columns=data['feature_names'])
sc = StandardScaler()
data = sc.fit_transform(df)

Compare transformed data with one, obtainable using PCA implementation from scikit-learn library.

In [ ]:
# Import libraries
from mpl_toolkits import mplot3d
pca = PCA(3)
pca.fit(data)
downSampledData = pca.transform(data)
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(12, 12))
ax = fig.gca(projection='3d')
ax.plot_trisurf(downSampledData.T[0],downSampledData.T[1],downSampledData.T[2])
plt.title("My PCA result")
plt.show()
In [ ]:
# write your code here
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA as sk_PCA
sk_pca = sk_PCA(3)
sk_pca.fit(data)
downSampledData = sk_pca.transform(data)
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(12, 12))
ax = fig.gca(projection='3d')
# for x,y,z in 
ax.plot_trisurf(downSampledData.T[0],downSampledData.T[1],downSampledData.T[2])
plt.title("SciKit Learn PCA result")
plt.show()

Task 2. Basis faces (3 points)¶

Retrieve the data of the face dataset (archive, folder). There are multiple face pictures in the context. The main thing is that faces are usually in the center of the image, so we may consider center of pictures to be samples from "face" subspace of an image space.

Your task is to find appropriate basis for that "face" subspace using PCA you implemented.

import glob

from PIL import Image

N=1000
SIZE=(50,50)
def img2vec(path):
  # img = plt.imread(path)
  # return img.flatten()
  img = Image.open(path)
  img = img.resize(SIZE,Image.ANTIALIAS)
  return np.array(img).flatten()

subspace = np.array([img2vec(dir) for dir in glob.glob('/content/lfw_funneled/*/*.jpg')[:]]).T

from numpy.ma.core import reshape
# write your code here
shape=(50,50,3)

def vec2img(vec):
  new_vec = vec.reshape(shape) 
  new_vec+= abs(np.min(new_vec))
  new_vec-= np.min(new_vec)
  new_vec /= np.max(new_vec)

  return new_vec

N_BASIS = 64
N_ROWS = 8


from mpl_toolkits.axes_grid1 import ImageGrid


fig = plt.figure(figsize=(16., 16.))
grid = ImageGrid(fig, 111, 
                 nrows_ncols=(N_BASIS//N_ROWS,N_ROWS),
                 axes_pad=0.1,)

for ax, im in zip(grid, [ vec2img(reduced_subspace[(i+1)*(j+1)-1]) 
  for i in range(N_BASIS//N_ROWS)
    for j in range(N_ROWS)]):
  ax.imshow(im)

plt.show()

As you may notice, many basis faces have negative elements, although the data itself is purely non-negative. Why is it so, why do we have negative elements from mathematical point of view? In what cases negative elements may be absent in PCA projection vectors?

Because in PCA we are interested in the eigenvectors of the subspace which has the larget covarince. in process of calculation of covariance matrix and centralization of the data(shifting the data by offset e.g mean) we will end up with posetive and negative and non-integer values.

There are matrix decompositions, that may be more useful than SVD in particular cases. For example, non-negative matrix factorization. You should implement it and use at the face dataset.

In [ ]:
# write your code here
epsilon = 1e-10
def get_H(W, H, V):
    return H*((W.T.dot(V)) / (W.T.dot(W).dot(H) + epsilon))
    
def get_W(W, H, V):
    return W*((V.dot(H.T)) / (W.dot(H).dot(H.T) +epsilon))
    
def nnmf(V, rank, iter):

    # Initialize
    n, m = V.shape

    W = np.abs(np.random.randn(1, n, rank))[0]
    H = np.abs(np.random.randn(1, rank, m))[0]

    loss = []
    for i in range(iter):
        H = get_H(W, H, V)
        W = get_W(W, H, V)

        loss.append(sum((V - W.dot(H)).flatten()**2))

    return H, W, loss
H,W,loss = nnmf(subspace,N_EIGFACE,10)

I can observer that PCA results in a clear results since it utilizes analytical solution for obtaining the components of the face subspace meanwhile NNMF basis are more noisy due to small number of iterations and big loss. however this loss can approach to zero by increment of the iterations.
